  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT350-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">pirivu nērnta talaimakaḷ avaṉatu nīkkattukkaṇ vēṟupaṭṭārait tōḻi
          vaṟpuṟīiyatu. </p>


        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">The confidante encouraging the one who was unchanged at
          his departure, [namely] SHE, who had granted separation. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT350">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> amma vāḻi tōḻi muṉṉiṉṟu</l>
          <l> paṉikkaṭuṅ kuraiyañ cellā tīmeṉac</l>
          <l> colliṉa māyiṟ celvar kollō</l>
          <l> vāṟṟaya lirunta viruntōṭ ṭañciṟai</l>
          <l> neṭunkāṟ kaṇantu ḷāḷaṟi vuṟīi</l>
          <l> yāṟucel vampalar paṭaitalai peyarkku</l>
          <l> malaiyuṭaik kāṉa nīnti</l>
          <l> nilaiyāp poruṭpiṇip pirintici ṉōrē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Alas, oh friend,</l>
          <l>would he have gone, if we had said <note place="foot">
            <term xml:lang="ta"> colliṉam </term>: this perfective aspect might mark the hypothetical character of the conditional. We know it must have been in the past because of the <term xml:lang="ta"> pirinticiṉōr </term>. So, in order not to have to understand <term xml:lang="ta">  celvar</term>  as a past tense, we have to explain it as a (tenseless) participial noun, i.e. literally "[would] he [have been] one who goes". </note>, confronting [him],</l>
        <l>“Don't go. We are such who cry out quick with [eye] dew.<note place="foot"> That is, SHE threatens to cry, as is usual in the case of HIS imminent departure. Since the  <term xml:lang="ta"> kurai</term> forms are rare, this might even be an allusion to 132.1, in a pronominal function: she will change from the one he makes happy by his embraces to one dissolved in tears.    </note> ”,</l>
        <l>he, who has separated enticed by impermanent wealth,</l>
        <l rend="indent">passing mountainous forests,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">where the travellers going the way bring [their] weapons</l>
        <l rend="indent8">in position,<note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> talaippeyar-ttal </term>: what does this mean? According to the TL, it is a lexeme "to redeem, recover", which does not seem helpful here. T.V.G. reads "they move [their] troops from [that] place, i.e. they choose a different route in order to avoid potential danger.  </note> </l>
        <l rend="indent3">informed about [the coming] of men by long-legged Kaṇantuḷ birds</l>
        <l rend="indent4">with pretty wings, in a big mass perched by the way?</l>


      </lg>
    </div>
